<DOCNO> AP880217-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-88 0406EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     02-17 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on Short-Term T-Bills Edge Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities edged up in the latest auction to the highest level in
two weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
Tuesday at an average discount rate of 5.73 percent, up from 5.63
percent last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.03 percent, up from 5.85 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since Feb. 1, when three-month bills
sold for 5.74 percent and six-month bills averaged 6.11 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 5.91 percent for three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,855.20 and 6.32 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,695.20.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Tuesday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, fell to 6.59
percent last week after averaging 6.65 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
