<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-88 0740EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AFL-CIO     02-17 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AFL-CIO,0443</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American labor leaders are breaking a
four-decade tradition of unqualified support for Israel, condemning
its use of ''unneccessary force'' against Palestinians on the West
Bank and in Gaza.
   The 14.3-million-member labor federation's executive council
approved the first-ever rebuke of Israel Tuesday after meeting with
Secretary of State George Shultz, who is scheduled to begin a tour
of the Middle East next week.
   The AFL-CIO's winter meeting was Shultz' last stop of an
extended weekend in southern Florida to gain support from
traditional friends of Israel for his effort to soften Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's opposition to entering new peace
negotiations.
   Shultz is seeking to promote a resumption of negotiations on
Palestinian self-rule in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   Shultz addressed a meeting of the B'Nai B'rith Anti-Defamation
League in Palm Beach last Friday, seeking help from U.S. Jewish
leaders in pressing Shamir to show more flexibility.
   ``There's been so much emphasis on the process ... direct
negotiations on the one hand, an international conference or some
kind of international vehicle on the other ... that the discussion
has become a little sterile,'' he told reporters Tuesday. ``If we
are going to get going, we need to talk a little bit more about the
substance of what might happen.''
   Shamir has opposed a resumption of negotiations if they are
based on a premise that Israel will have to give up state control
of some of the occupied territories as a condition for peace.
   Shultz said the United States is ``not trying to stake out a
position of one kind or another'' on that issue. However, he said
getting ``to the substance in terms of things ... that would be
talked about when people address ultimate resolutions of the
Arab-Israeli conflict'' is needed to get the negotiations going
again.
   The AFL-CIO, while blaming Islamic fundamentalists for ``fueling
the flames of violence in the occupied territories,'' said the
Palestinian demonstrations did not warrant the ``unnecessary
force'' used by Israeli defense forces on occasion.
   ``No doubt such incidents can be attributed to the inexperience
of the Israeli army in riot control and other police functions, and
to the frustrations of Israeli soldiers as they confront young
Palestinians hurling stones and petrol bombs,'' the federation
said. ``These factors may explain, but they cannot excuse, and the
AFL-CIO cannot condone, the use of excessive force against
civilians.''
   The federation, however, rejected what it called a ``notion that
Israel must now redeem itself by turning the West Bank and Gaza
Strip over to the Palestine Liberation Organization.''
</TEXT>
