<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Clash     02-17 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Clash,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Lebanon Clash Kills 17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem guerrillas
and pro-Israeli militiamen fought for six hours in south Lebanon
today, leaving at least 17 fighters dead and four wounded.
   A police spokesman said the two sides used rockets, mortars, and
automatic rifles in the clash south of the Christian town of
Jezzine, 10 miles east of the port city of Sidon.
   He said seven fighters of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
militia were killed and four wounded when Shiite Moslem guerillas
of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, ambushed their
patrol at 6 a.m. outside Jezzine.
   The South Lebanon Army ``sent reinforcements to the area and
fought a six-hour battle killing 10 attackers,'' said the
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity according to
regulations.
   He said that after the killing of its fighters, Hezbollah
pounded the battle scene, two miles southeast of Jezzine, with
mortar fire. It later recovered the bodies of six of its men.
   The South Lebanon Army is based in a six-mile deep
Israeli-occupied border strip in south Lebanon and carries out
frequent patrols into Jezzine, a Christian town outside the zone.
   Israel established the so-called security zone along the border
after the withdrawal of the bulk of its occupation army from south
Lebanon in 1985, three years after it invaded the country.
   Hezbollah comprises Shiite zealots, who are backed by Iran's
Islamic revolution.
</TEXT>
