<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscar-Reax,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Television and Telephone Calls Break Oscar News to Nominees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oscar Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another Dukakis entered the race, actress
Holly Hunter slept through the broadcast and Steven Spielberg
wasn't talking after Wednesday's Oscar nominations were announced.
   ``Like my cousin, I'm in the running and now I'm waiting for
`Super Monday' in April,'' said Olympia Dukakis after her
supporting actress nomination for ``Moonstruck'' was announced.
   Hours earlier, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis won the
Democratic New Hampshire primary.
   Nominees were announced at dawn in Beverly Hills by actress
Shirley MacLaine and Robert Wise, president of the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences. The timing was tailored for live
East Coast network coverage.
   Miss Dukakis' reaction to her nomination was captured by
``Entertainment Tonight'' TV cameras. ``Broadcast News''
writer-director James L. Brooks was dressing in a Berlin hotel when
he learned of the film's seven nominations.
   Tony Huston was awakened at his Beverly Hills home by publicist
Sheila Barr and told about his best screenplay nomination for ``The
Dead.'' His father, director John Huston, died last year while
working on the film.
   Tony Huston recalled his father's advice years ago to another
Oscar nominee who didn't know what to say to reporters. The senior
Huston said: ``Don't say _ listen.''
   Albert Brooks was in the Southern California desert writing the
screenplay for his next movie when he heard he'd been nominated in
the best supporting actor category for his role as a TV reporter in
``Broadcast News.''
   ``I'm on my way out to see the movie again to see what they are
talking about,'' Brooks said through manager Herb Nanas.
   ``Broadcast News'' writer-director Brooks was at the Berlin Film
Festival and was told of the seven nominations in a telephone call
from publicist Pat Kingsley. Brooks also was overlooked in the
director category.
   The publicist said Miss Hunter was asleep hours after her
nomination was announced.
   Italian director Bernardo Bertolucci said his nomination for
``The Last Emperor'' was ``like passing exams at school _ the
sensation of becoming an adult.''
   ``I think this is the victory of a film that only wants to be
cinema, that is not intimidated by television, that believes in the
great screen, in cinema as the cathedral of collective
imagination,'' Bertolucci said in Rome.
   Best director nominee Adrian Lyne said he still finds it tough
to believe people liked his movie ``Fatal Attraction.''
   ``I got up early, fearing and trembling, watching the live thing
on CNN,'' Lyne said. When the movie came up in category after
category, ``I was bouncing up and down with my wife and the dog.''
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' said Glenn Close, nominated for her role as a
vengeful, psychotic woman in ``Fatal Attraction,'' which she said
``represents the work of an extraordinary team of people.''
   Miss Close was at her New York country home when informed about
her nomination.
   Douglas, best actor nominee for ``Wall Street,'' sat in the den
of his New York apartment to watch the announcement of his first
acting nomination on television.
   ``I watched this morning and I looked at the names and
photographs of my fellow nominees and it made me not only proud for
our film `Wall Street' but it reminded me what a wonderful part
(writer-director) Oliver Stone had created,'' Douglas said.
</TEXT>
