<FILEID>AP-NR-02-17-88 1025EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     02-17 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0329</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced broadly today,
extending the rally it began a week ago.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 110.25 points over
the past five sessions, rose 1.82 to 2,007.79 in the first half
hour today.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in the early
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 807 up, 350
down and 496 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 29.30 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said optimism about the economic outlook had gradually
been increasing in recent days.
   On Tuesday Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board, described economic activity as stable if not especially
``buoyant.''
   There was some disappointment in the financial world over
Greenspan's remarks implying that the Fed had no plans for any
further relaxation of its credit policy.
   But brokers said that message also meant that policymakers saw
no great cause for concern about an impending recession.
   At the same time, numerous takeover developments and rumors have
revived some of the enthusiasm for stocks that vanished in the
crash last fall.
   Firestone Tire & Rubber dropped 2 to 43 after jumping 9\ points
on Tuesday, when the company agreed to form a joint venture with
Bridgestone Corp. of Japan that would take over Firestone's tire
business.
